3. Tokenization
Note: The codebase does NOT implement custom tokenization. Instead, it relies on:

LLM Provider Tokenization
LiteLLM Integration:
Uses LiteLLM library which handles tokenization internally
Different models (GPT-4, GPT-3.5, Azure OpenAI) use their native tokenizers
Token Counting:
Tracked in LLM response metadata:
prompt_tokens
completion_tokens
total_tokens
No Explicit Tokenization Code:
The system doesn't manually tokenize text
Relies on the LLM provider's tokenizer (e.g., tiktoken for OpenAI models)
Token limits are configured per model in pipeline config
Context Window Management
Instead of tokenization, the system uses text truncation strategies:

Document Chunking:
Documents are pre-chunked in ServiceNow backend
Each chunk has chunk_text and chunk_score
Chunks are selected based on relevance scores
Prompt Construction:
Preprocessors assemble context from top-ranked chunks
Limits are based on character count or chunk count
No explicit token counting before LLM call
Summary
RAG Flow:

User Query
    ↓
PLANNER2_RETRIEVAL
    ├─ Fetch from KB/Catalog/Skills/External
    ├─ Get user attachments
    ├─ Rerank documents (parallel)
    └─ Store in execution_context
    ↓
PLANNER2
    ├─ Wait for parallel tasks (web search, KG NLQ)
    ├─ Preprocess (build prompt with context)
    ├─ LLM call (streaming enabled)
    ├─ Postprocess (extract citations)
    └─ Return answer
MCP Role:

Protocol for tool execution
Handles authentication & routing
Standardized request/response format
Supports both internal (ServiceNow) and external tools
Tokenization:

Handled by LLM provider (not custom)
No explicit tokenization in orchestrator
Context managed via chunk selection and text truncation
